data.content:
All working. Here's what the program demonstrates:

### `GetTypeInfo<T>()` — strongly-typed metadata
Returns a `JsonTypeInfo<T>` directly (no cast needed). We use it to serialize a `WeatherForecast` through the typed overload of `JsonSerializer.Serialize`.

### `TryGetTypeInfo<T>(out JsonTypeInfo<T>?)` — probe without throwing
Returns `bool` — `true` + the typed info when the resolver knows the type, `false` when it doesn't. No `try/catch` required. The demo shows this by using an **empty** resolver (`JsonTypeInfoResolver.Combine()` with no arguments) that can't resolve `UnknownThing`.

Both APIs are new in .NET 11 on `JsonSerializerOptions`.

<details><summary>Final Program.cs</summary>

```csharp
using System.Text.Json;
using System.Text.Json.Serialization;
using System.Text.Json.Serialization.Metadata;

var options = new JsonSerializerOptions(JsonSerializerDefaults.Web)
{
    TypeInfoResolver = new DefaultJsonTypeInfoResolver()
};

// 1. GetTypeInfo<T>() — strongly-typed
JsonTypeInfo<WeatherForecast> typeInfo = options.GetTypeInfo<WeatherForecast>();
string json = JsonSerializer.Serialize(new WeatherForecast("Seattle", 62), typeInfo);

// 2. TryGetTypeInfo<T>() — safe probe
options.TryGetTypeInfo<WeatherForecast>(out var resolved);   // → true
var empty = new JsonSerializerOptions { TypeInfoResolver = JsonTypeInfoResolver.Combine() };
empty.TryGetTypeInfo<UnknownThing>(out _);                   // → false, no exception

public record WeatherForecast(string City, int TempF);
public record UnknownThing(string Data);
```
</details>
